elements.content: Using a rigid ligand, 4-(5-(pyridin-4-yl)-4H-1,2,4-triazol-3-yl) benzoic acid (HL), three metal(II)–organic frameworks (MOFs) formulated as M2L4·3H2O [M = Co (1), Cu (2), and Zn (3)] were synthesized and characterized by single-crystal X-ray diffraction. The three MOFs are isostructural except for different unsaturated coordinated metal(II) ions in the structures, and they display a uninodal two-dimensional layer with 44-sql topology. Among the three complexes, the Co and Cu complexes can act as electrocatalysts for water splitting, and the Co complex shows better electrocatalytic activity. The present work shows that the species of metal(II) ions plays an important role in the electrocatalytic activity for water splitting. The three complexes show different thermal stabilities, UV–vis absorption characteristics, and photoluminescence properties.

Coordination to metals usually can stabilize these energetic intermediates, thereby lowering the overpotentials for the evolutions of oxygen and hydrogen.

elements.content: In the present work, we synthesized a rigid ligand, 4-(5-(pyridin-4-yl)-4H −1,2,4-triazol-3-yl) benzoic acid (HL) (Scheme ), in which the rigid pyridine ring, 1H-1,2,4-triazole moiety, and carboxylic acid species coexist, and the ligand is expected to be stable for water splitting. Herein, hydrothermal reactions of metal(II) salts with HL resulted in three metal(II) complexes formulated as M2L4·3H2O [M = Co (1), Cu (2), and Zn (3)] in moderate yields. As the ultimate goal for water splitting is to couple the electrocatalyst systems for the two halves of the water-splitting reaction (water oxidation and proton reduction) into an integrated efficient catalyst system, the electrocatalytic properties of the three complexes toward the H2 evolution reaction (HER) and oxygen evolution reaction (OER) from water have been investigated. They were found to exhibit different electrocatalytic behaviors, thermal stabilities, UV–vis absorption spectra, emission spectra, and photoluminescence lifetimes.

Experimental Section

General Considerations

The ligand HL was prepared according to the literature method. The other starting materials were commercially available and were used as received. Elemental analyses (C, H, and N) were carried out on an Elementar Vario MICRO E III analyzer. FT-IR spectra were obtained from KBr pellets on a Perkin-Elmer spectrometer. Powder XRD (PXRD) data were recorded using Cu Kα radiation on a Rigaku DMAX2500PC diffractometer. Thermal analyses were measured on a NETZSCH STA 449C thermogravimetric analyzer at a heating rate of 10 °C⋅min-1 under N2 atmosphere. UV-vis spectra were collected on a Hitachi U-4100 UV-vis spectrophotometer. The emission spectra of the solid samples were measured at room temperature on an Edinburgh FLS920 fluorescence spectrometer using an Edinburgh Xe900 xenon arc lamp as the exciting light source. The photoluminescence lifetime was recorded on an Edinburgh Lifespec fluorescence spectrometer with a 372-nm laser as the exciting light source.

elements.content: In conclusion, using the rigid ligand HL, three metal(II)–L complexes have been synthesized and characterized by single-crystal X-ray diffraction. The three complexes are isostructural but contain different metal(II) ions. They display a uninodal two-dimensional layer with a 44-sql topology and two such (4,4) nets interpenetrate in a parallel manner. Co complex 1 and Cu complex 2 can act as electrocatalysts toward the HER and OER from water, with Co complex 2 exhibiting better electrocatalytic activity. Zn complex 3 cannot function as an eletrocatalyst for water splitting. The present work shows that the species of metal(II) ions plays an important role in the electrocatalytic activity. This is probably because of the different unsaturated coordinated metal centers in the structures for the binding of intermediate species. Investigation of the detailed mechanism is underway. The three complexes exhibit different thermal stabilities, UV–vis absorption spectra, emission spectra, and photoluminescence lifetimes.

Conclusions

In conclusion, using the rigid ligand HL, three metal(II)-L complexes have been synthesized and characterized by single-crystal X-ray diffraction. The three complexes are isostructural but contain different metal(II) ions. They display a uninodal two-dimensional layer with a 44-sql topology and two such (4,4) nets interpenetrate in a parallel manner. Co complex 1 and Cu complex 2 can act as electrocatalysts toward the HER and OER from water, with Co complex 2 exhibiting better electrocatalytic activity. Zn complex 3 cannot function as an eletrocatalyst for water splitting. The present work shows that the species of metal(II) ions plays an important role in the electrocatalytic activity. This is probably because of the different unsaturated coordinated metal centers in the structures for the binding of intermediate species. Investigation of the detailed mechanism is underway. The three complexes exhibit different thermal stabilities, UV-vis absorption spectra, emission spectra, and photoluminescence lifetimes.
